The Central Bank of Kenya (CBK) has today opened an ultra-modern cash-clearing unit in Kisii, to cater for financial needs of the wider Nyanza and Kisii region. This development takes place owing to a growing number of financial institutions in the region. The CBK has set up this money clearing centre in Kisii town at the ground and second floor of the Absa Bank Kisii branch. Already, CBK has branches in Mombasa, Kisumu and Eldoret as well as Currency Centres in Nyeri, Nakuru and Meru. These Branches and Currency Centres form a critical point for currency distribution to regional financial institutions. The Kisii Centre was officially opened today by President Uhuru Kenyatta in the presence of the CBK Governor Dr Patrick Njoroge and senior Kisii County Government officials. The Kisii Centre, the 4th such facility, is expected to support CBKâ€™s currency operations across 7 Counties in the region. This cash centre is expected to be involved in the distribution of notes and coins to commercial banks in the region. The new currency centre in Kisii has been launched in collaboration with ABSA Bank Kenya, where the two institutions will share common facilities. â€œAll county governments will get better services from this centerâ€ said CBK Governor Dr Patrick Njoroge. He added that the technology in this centre is world-class. The facility has a solar roof that will generate more energy with any excess energy fed to the national grid where it will be able to sustain up to 160 homes. The centre is expected to support smooth banking operations for both the private sector and public institutions in the region.

KUCHING, Nov 12 -- The Sarawak State Assembly (DUN) today passed a Bill to amend Article 16 of the State Constitution to lower the minimum age required for a person to become an elected representative from 21 to 18 years old. The Constitution of the State of Sarawak (Amendment) Bill, 2020, which was tabled by the State Youth and Sports Minister, Datuk Abdul Karim Rahman Hamzah was passed with more than a two-thirds majority as only nine assembly members were against it. He originally tabled a similar Bill last Tuesday but Speaker Datuk Amar Mohd Asfia Awang Nassar decided to defer it as there were â€œobviously anomalies in definitionsâ€ in the Bill that had to be addressed then. Announcing the withdrawal of the original Bill today to pave the way for the new one, Abdul Karim said it was done to avoid the people of Sarawak from being confused by the Opposition as to the real intent and objective of the amendment. â€œThis Bill which I am now introducing will remove all interpretative ambiguities or uncertainties as to the real intent and objective of the proposed amendments,â€ he said when tabling the bill. Abdul Karim said that the amendment would align the State Constitution with the amended Article 47(b) and Article 119(1)(a) of the Federal Constitution which had reduced the qualifying age for the election to the Dewan Rakyat and to be an elector or voter, from 21 years old to 18 years old. â€œArticle 16 of the State Constitution complies with the mandatory provision in Section 5 of the Eighth Schedule of the Federal Constitution which sets out the qualification of Members of a State Legislative Assembly,â€ he said. For the second part of the Article 16 of the State Constitution, which had been the focus of the debate for the Bill, the amendment would see only two categories of persons qualified to be defined as â€œresident in the Stateâ€. They are citizens born in the State whose parents or either of them was also born in the State and normally residing in the State; or citizens, though not born in the State, whose parents or either of them was born in the State and normally residing in the State. â€œPeople with no Sarawakian connection either by birth or the birth of their parents and not normally resident in Sarawak will be disqualified,â€ he added. -- BERNAMA

MotoGP - Gran Premio italiano - Circuito del Mugello, Scarperia, Italia - 2 giugno 2019 della Ducati di Danilo Petrucci e del Repsol Honda Marc Marquez a (Reuters) - Ducati di Danilo Petrucci ha ottenuto la sua vittoria in MotoGP inaugurale davanti ai suoi tifosi di casa al Gran Premio italiano a Mugello Domenica. Il 2 anni di etÃ , che ha iniziato terza posizione in griglia, crociera alla vittoria in 41 minuti, 33.794 secondi di vantaggio su campione del mondo della Honda Marc Marquez e il suo compagno di squadra Andrea Dovizioso. In un incontro che pulsa, che ha visto le mani di cambiamento di piombo in diverse occasioni, Petrucci raccolse il suo momento nel giro finale di negare contendenti del campionato Marquez e Dovizioso. Il leader del campionato Marquez spostato fino a 115 punti nella classifica generale, davanti a Dovizioso (103) e Alex Rins di Suzuki (88), che ha chiuso la gara al quarto posto. (Segnalazione da Hardik Vyas a Bangalore, la modifica da Pritha Sarkar)

PETALING JAYA: An additional three roadblocks have been set up at PLUS highway toll plazas on the seventh day of the conditional movement control order (MCO) at the Subang, Putrajaya and Bandar Serenia toll plazas. This brings the total number of roadblocks to 27 locations. Prior to this 24 were announced at toll plazas in Jalan Duta, Setia Alam, Shah Alam, Putra Mahkota, Sungai Buaya, Bukit Tagar, Bukit Beruntung and Lembah Beringin. Roadblocks have also been set up at Seafield, Rawang, Tanjung Malim, Bukit Raja, Kajang, Bangi, USJ, Putra Heights, Bandar Saujana Putra as well as at Sungai Buloh, Hospital Sungai Buloh, Rawang South, Damansara, Sungai Besi, KL International Airport and Southville City. Additionally, PLUS announced that all suraus located at its rest stops in Kuala Lumpur, Putrajaya and Selangor will be closed during the conditional MCO period.

KUALA LUMPUR â€“ Yayasan Basmi Kemiskinan (YBK) melancarkan logo baharu sempena sambutan ke-20 yayasan itu yang ditubuhkan pada Mac 1990. Sepanjang beroperasi, YBK telah menyantuni ribuan anak yatim, keluarga miskin, orang kurang upaya (OKU) dan belia tercicir di seluruh negara. Menurut Pengerusinya, Datuk Zainal Abidin Sakom, dalam usaha menjadi sebuah yayasan yang mantap dan berkesan, YBK telah melaksanakan pelbagai program berteraskan sosio ekonomi serta pendidikan. Kata beliau, logo baharu yang dilancarkan semalam adalah pemenang kepada pertandingan mencipta Logo 30 Tahun YBK yang dilangsungkan November lalu. Katanya, rekaan logo 30 tahun itu diilhamkan daripada logo YBK itu sendiri iaitu warna biru, merah dan kuning, manakala angka 30 adalah simbolik semangat juang kental dan berjiwa besar bagi memastikan YBK kekal relevan di mata masyarakat. â€œTambahan warna hijau pula adalah simbol warna 30 tahun dan reben yang mengelilingi logo tersebut melambangkan jalinan â€˜ukhwah fillahâ€™ antara sahabat YBK yang bersama dalam suka duka sejak 1990 sehingga 2020. â€œPada awal penubuhannya, YBK melihat punca utama masalah kemiskinan di Selangor ketika itu disebabkan keluarga miskin tiada tempat berteduh yang kondusif. â€œJusteru, YBK mengorak langkah dan mengambil inisiatif sehingga terbinalah kira-kira 1,000 unit rumah di Lindungan Kasih di Sabak Bernam dan sembilan penempatan Desa Kasih di seluruh negeri,â€ katanya dalam kenyataan kepada Malaysia Gazette di sini, hari ini. Menurut Zainal Abidin, penubuhan Asrama Kasih YBK di Serendah dan Gesir, Pusat Latihan di Kuala Selangor serta Akademi Kemahiran di Gesir pula menyaksikan 6,500 pelajar miskin dan belia tercicir berjaya dibantu dari segi peningkatan tahap pendidikan dan pembangunan sahsiah diri. Program Kumpulan Tuisyen Hujung Minggu (KUNTUM) dan Fastrack pula katanya, menyediakan tuisyen dan kelas secara tersusun kepada pelajar miskin terpilih di seluruh negara. â€œPeranan dan perjuangan YBK dilihat belum selesai. Ini kerana, melihat kos sara hidup pada ketika ini yang meningkat mengakibatkan kumpulan miskin meningkat khususnya miskin bandar dan B40. â€œDengan cabaran tahun 2020 dan pendekatan Revolusi Industri 4.0 banyak menekan dan mengakibatkan ramai kehilangan pekerjaan yang akhirnya membawa kepada hilangnya punca pendapatan. â€œOleh itu, YBK terus berfungsi melaksanakan pelbagai program tahunan berbentuk â€˜laman amalâ€™ bagi mendidik jiwa masyarakat untuk sama-sama berkongsi rasa dengan individu dan keluarga yang memerlukan,â€ katanya. Antara program itu kata Zainal Abidin ialah Santuni Gelandangan di Masjid Jamek Sultan Abdul Samad Kuala Lumpur; motivasi percuma kepada pelajar melalui Program Motivasi Semangat Mendaki. Program lain ialah Apabila Tibanya Ramadan dan Sinar Kasih Ramadan (SKR) yang menjadi fokus dengan YBK menyediakan keperluan belanja bersahur dan berbuka puasa bagi keluarga miskin terpilih. â€œKita juga menyediakan program â€˜YBK Eyeâ€™ iaitu pemberian cermin mata percuma kepada pelajar kurang berkemampuan di Selangor,â€ katanya. Justeru, beliau berharap rakyat Malaysia dapat bersama memberi sokongan dan menggembeleng usaha bagi mencapai aspirasi YBK untuk membasmi kemiskinan serta membina kesejahteraan hari ini dan di masa akan datang. â€“ MalaysiaGazette

Best Biotech Stocks to Buy for 2021 By: TheStreet | December 24, 2020 â€¢ Which biotech names will see magnified growth over the coming year? Real Money writer Bret Jensen reveals his top picks. Investing in biotech can be a bit of an experiment: I have profiled several small-cap biotech stocks that have grown into real monsters, and others that have gone dormant. The former include stocks such as Axsome Therapeutics (AXSM), Reata Pharmaceuticals (RETA) and Invitae (NVTA). The latter includes Synergy Pharma (SGYP). This is basically the roller coaster an investor can expect from this high-beta segment of the market. Few areas in equities are more volatile than small-cap biotech, biopharma and health care. Combined, these sectors produce more massive winners and horrid losers than any other area of the market. So, just as a scientist has to live with trial and error, the investor must be able to live with loser stocks. That's why diversification is key to staying sane and profitable over the long term. Still, the biotech sector has been on a real tear in recent months. I would not be surprised, in fact, if the sector saw some profit-taking at some point soon. Of course, I could say that about the overall market, which I currently see as overbought. That said, biotech should be well positioned in 2021. We should get back to "normalcy" at some point in the new year, and mergers and acquisitions will eventually pick up. We have seen a few large transactions in recent months already, including the $39 billion takeover of Alexion Pharmaceuticals (ALXN) by AstraZeneca (AZN), which was the largest deal in the sector for the year. What names should do well in 2021? Here are the ones I see getting let out of the cage: First is Heron Therapeutics (HRTX), a company I have mentioned a few times on Real Money this year. Sales of its anti-nausea drug Cinvanti should pick up as regular oncology procedures return to their normal pattern after getting hit in many areas of the country from lockdowns and other restrictions. In addition, its pain-relief compound Zynrelef should be approved by the Food and Drug Administration in the first half of 2021. The compound recently was approved in Europe. This should become a much more important product for the company than Cinvanti over time. Next up is Theravance Biopharma (TBPH). Covid-19 hurt the growth of Yupelri, which was approved in 2018. This product is the only once-daily, nebulized bronchodilator approved in the U.S. for the maintenance treatment of patients with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, or COPD. That drug should get back on track in 2021. In addition, royalty litigation around another product should be resolved in the coming year. The company also has several late-stage studies for other products whose data should hit next year. Add it all up, and you have a lot of potential positive catalysts for this biopharma name in the new year. Biohaven Pharmaceuticals (BHVN) is another name I'm watching. Biohaven has delivered in a big-time way for shareholders in 2020, but seems poised for more upside still in 2021. The company launched Nurtec ODT, which was earlier this year approved for acute migraines. By the third quarter, 220,000 prescriptions were written for the drug. Nurtec ODT looks to be a blockbuster in this part of the market. Now, the company is already working on another product in this space called Zavegepant, which in its oral form could prevent migraines and non-migraine headaches. Some key trials should post data in the first half of 2021, and, if all goes well, this compound could get FDA approval by a year from now. The company is also targeting three other drug launches, provided all goes well, in trials by 2023. With a market cap just north of $5.5 billion, this mid-cap company could end up on a larger playerâ€™s shopping list at some point. I also like Karyopharm Therapeutics (KPTI), as it is approaching the new year with some momentum. Its Xpovio drug has shown good sales growth in 2020. This compound was originally FDA-approved for the treatment of relapsed or refractory multiple myeloma -- a cancer of plasma cells -- and for some types of large B-cell lymphoma. The FDA earlier in December OK'd Xpovio in combination with bortezomib and dexamethasone for patients with multiple myeloma who tried at least one prior therapy. The compound has also showed good recent trial results in other oncology areas and appears set to be approved for other indications in 2021. I see this as another possible buyout target. On the Shelf, Ready to Go Finally, we have some holdovers, those names stuck on the lab's shelf that didnâ€™t do much in 2020, but should be good picks for 2021. BioDelivery Sciences (BDSI) has not gotten the credit it deserves for the impressive sales growth it has achieved from pain medicine Belbuca, since it got the marketing rights back for this product from Endo International (ENDP) at the end of 2017. In 2021, however, the company should be able churn out consistent profitability quarters and investors realize it is trading at approximately one-times peak annual revenue from its current product portfolio. Another name is Exelixis (EXEL), which posted a small gain in 2020, even as growth in its core kidney cancer treatment product Cabometyx took a hit from the pandemic. Cabometyx alone is an approximately $1 billion a year franchise. The compound is in trials for a variety of other uses that could triple to quintuple peak annual sales, according to management. The company also has approximately $1.5 billion in cash on the balance sheet, which the company plans to use to make small "bolt on" acquisitions, as good opportunities present themselves. That is if this approximately $6 billion market-cap company is not the target of a larger player first in 2021. Read Full Story Â»Â»Â» DiscoverGold

This hotel was never really my choice, but my girlfriend persuaded me to go and I just came to tell you all that I regret that. In the first minute we walk into the room there was an odd, unpleasant smell, hard to describe it - like very old air, like the room was not cleaned properly or refreshed. The TV is good to be thrown out the window, 'cause the image was so poor and the remote control so warn that they really have no other use. Getting in and out of the room was always an ordeal, the keys (yeah, they gave us 2 identical keys) never worked well, I'm telling you, sometimes I spent 3-5 minutes just to close the damn door. We had breakfast included in price and they say they have a 4* restaurant - what a joke ... Food was scarce, not really that tasty. Even the juice was full of water, almost tasteless. Sunday morning before 7 a.m. we were all (4 persons) woken up by an unbelievable loud noise coming from somewhere beneath us (we stayed at 1st floor). When we left I asked the front-desk guy what was that awful sound, he smiled (never apologized) and told me that he knows very well what it was - hood from the kitchen. He told us that when we come back, we should ask for rooms above 2nd floor, at least, or we will be given the same awful awakening ... I saved the worst for the end : one friend of mine passed out when taking a shower with cold water after he just emerged from salt-water pool, which had hot water. He really bashed his head and shoulder on the floor, we spent the next 7-8 hours in Emergency in Tg. Mures, the nearest town. When I first announced the staff of the accident, I thought they will announce their doctor and this guy will surely help my friend. Well, it turned out that they don't have a doctor for accidents, the woman that played that role from the hotel was giving him water and told him to lay down. Basically, it goes like this : if you have the misfortune to suffer an injury while you use their facilities, your only chance is if you are lucky enough. If you're not, then pray for that ambulance to come faster, the staff of the hotel will not help you with anything more than a glass of water and a band aid. They were willing to help us, I'm not saying otherwise, it's just that they're simply not qualified or prepared for anything serious. They didn't know what to do, were looking at me and asking me "should we call the ambulance" while my friend was dripping blood from his chin. I had to tell them "yes, call the ambulance", as if it was not alarming enough seeing him hitting that floor so hard. The next day, one of the employees from the pool-bar told my girlfriend that passing out after emerging from hot, salt water was not that uncommon, they had several accidents over the years. What did they did to prevent others happening ? Pretty much nothing, they had a metal plate next to the showers warning people with blood-pressure affections about the possible danger. That's it, a plate. My friend is still alive 'cause he was lucky enough not to hit the steep, rocky ledge that's very close to the showers. Well, I learned my lesson on this one, but if you still want to go I wish you best of luck.

(Video) 'Dia menangis tanpa henti...'- Calon SPM tatap wajah jenazah bapanya kali terakhir sebelum sambung exam Tatkala calon Sijil Pelajaran Malaysia (SPM) lain sedang menjawab kertas peperiksaan, Muhammad Haikal Iskandar Zamry, 18, menangisi pemergian bapanya di perkarangan sekolah dan menatap wajah bapa kesayangannya itu buat kali terakhir sebelum masuk ke dewan peperiksaan. Guru bimbingan dan kaunseling SMK Simpang Beluru, Badariah Mohd Mohaidin berkata, pelajar itu diberi kesempatan untuk berbuat demikian selepas ibunya mencadangkan jenazah suaminya dibawa ke sekolah, memandangkan anaknya yang terikat dengan jadual peperiksaan tidak memungkinkannya untuk menatap jenazah bapa buat kali terakhir. Difahamkan, bapa pelajar itu pada awalnya koma semasa dirawat di Hospital Taiping sejak beberapa hari lalu akibat komplikasi buah pinggang, selain jangkitan kuman dalam darah. Haikal langsung tidak berpeluang untuk menziarahi bapanya atas sebab SOP yang dikenakan bagi mengekang wabak Covid-19. "Arwah meninggal dunia semalam, namun baru hari ini jenazah dibenarkan keluar dari hospital untuk dikebumikan. Bagiamanapun Haikal tetap ingin menduduki kertas hari ini walaupun sedia tahu ayahnya sudah tiada. "Ketibaan van jenazah ke sekolah sememangnya untuk beri peluang kepada Haikal menatap wajah arwah buat kali terakhir memandangkan peperiksaan yang didudukinya sehingga petang.. "Jika Haikal balik rumah untuk menghadiri pengebumian ayahnya, memang tidak sempat. Bahkan Haikal terlewat 20 minit berbanding calon lain yang sudah menduduki kertas Sejarah 2 ketika menghabiskan masa menatap arwah bapanya itu," katanya. Haikal merupakan anak sulung dari tiga beradik dari keluarga yang kurang berkemampuan. Sebelum ketibaan van jenazah itu, Haikal ditenangkan oleh guru-gurunya yang melihat dia menangis tanpa henti pada waktu rehat, selain menyediakan bilik khas untuk dirinya bertenang dan melepaskan emosi yang tidak begitu stabil.

JEMPOL: Two more Thais were arrested in Perlis today, bringing to eight the number of Thai nationals nabbed for the fatal shootout at the Malaysia-Thailand border yesterday, said Inspector-General of Police Tan Sri Abdul Hamid Bador. He said the duo were arrested at 7am at the border wall in Padang Besar, bringing to four the number of Thais nabbed in Malaysian territory after the shootout. The other four suspects were arrested by Thai authorities in Thailand yesterday. "We believe these two Thais could not escape because they failed to find a way to get past the border wall. So, when we (security forces) conducted a sweep in the farms and bushes, we came upon these two. "They have been taken for further questioning. We are in talks and will make an official application to the Royal Thai Police to hand over to us the four arrested in Thailand to face justice (in Malaysia)," he told reporters after attending the burial of Corporal Baharuddin Ramli, 54, who was killed in the shootout with smugglers early yesterday. Hamid said the Criminal Investigation Department, with the help of a forensics team, was combing the area to look for the weapons used by the group of smugglers. The smugglers might have dumped their firearms in the bushes in their haste to escape after the shootout, he added. "They are probably waiting for the situation to quieten down before attempting to cross the border wall; the two nabbed this morning were trying to do that," he said. Asked how many more suspects police were looking for, he said investigators would get the answer only after they have finished questioning those arrested. "Some information said more than 10â€¦ maybe 12, 13 or 14, but we are not sure," he said. Baharuddin, from the 3rd Battalion (Senoi Praaq) of the Northern Brigade GOF, and his colleague Corporal Norihan Tari, 39, were on intelligence-gathering rounds when they stumbled upon the smugglers. Norihan was seriously wounded in the shootout and admitted to Hospital Tuanku Fauziah in Kangar where he underwent surgery yesterday evening. Earlier today, Hamid spent about two hours visiting the family of Baharuddin and also to pay his last respects to the slain policeman, who was buried at the Orang Asli cemetery in Kampung Sungai Sampo, Bandar Sri Jempol here. Baharuddin was laid to rest at 12.20pm, with hundreds of people comprising family members, relatives, villagers and police personnel attending his funeral. - Bernama

Selepas empat bulan berlalu, ibu kepada penyanyi Sandra Dianne mengakui semangatnya kini sudah kembali kuat atas berkat doa daripada ahli keluarga dan peminat arwah anak perempuannya. Biarpun Sandra atau nama sebenarnya Alessandra Dianne Ampuria sudah tiada, namun Syakinah, 45, tetap mahu melakukan sesuatu untuk saham akhirat buat Allahyarham. Menurut Syakinah yang menetap di Sabah, dia ada menjual baju T dan buku nota di laman sosial dan hasil jualan tersebut disedekahkan kepada pihak tertentu untuk tujuan wakaf. "Alhamdulillah... saya dah move on dan bersyukur sebab ramai orang di sekeliling yang memberi semangat terutama ahli keluarga dan peminat arwah Sandra. "Berkat doa semua orang. Peminat arwah tidak berhenti tanya khabar dan beri semangat di laman sosial. Ujian ini membuatkan saya lebih dekat dan sentiasa ingat Allah. "Saya ada buat beberapa perancangan untuk bekalan arwah. Setakat ini, ada menjual baju t shirt dan notebook arwah di laman sosial dan hasil jualan tersebut dibuat sebagai wakaf," katanya kepada mStar. Syakinah berkongsi perkara tersebut ketika sesi pelancaran video muzik lagu terbaharu arwah anaknya berjudul SANDRA secara maya pada Rabu. Dalam pada itu, Syakinah turut memuji individu yang membawa watak sebagai Sandra dengan baik sehingga dia tidak dapat menahan air matanya daripada mengalir disebabkan terbayang arwah anak perempuannya masih ada. Syakinah juga mengakui dia berasa terkejut apabila mengetahui Sandra sudah menunaikan hasratnya untuk membawa lagu genre R&B soul yang pertama kali dinyanyikan oleh Allahyarham. "Pertama sekali, saya ucapkan tahniah kepada individu yang membawa watak Sandra dalam video muzik tersebut. Dia berjaya membawa watak arwah dengan baik. "Lengong badan dan cara dia libas rambut itu seolah-olah memang arwah. Saya tak boleh fokus tempat lain, hanya fokus kepada dia sebab membayangkan arwah masih ada. "Sebenarnya saya agak terkejut sebab arwah tak pernah nak bawa genre lagu seperti itu. Tapi saya pernah suarakan hasrat untuk arwah bawa lagu genre itu. Tak sangka arwah tunaikan hasrat saya dalam diam," ujarnya. Sandra yang juga bekas peserta Big Stage 2020 a meninggal dunia pada 11 September lalu selepas enam hari bertarung nyawa di unit rawatan rapi (ICU), Hospital Putrajaya. Pada 5 September tahun lalu, Allahyarham terbabit dalam kemalangan Lebuh Raya Utara Selatan Hubungan Tengah (Elite) berhampiran Subang Jaya, ketika dalam perjalanan mengikuti latihan konsert minggu keempat Big Stage di Pusat Konvensyen Antarabangsa Putrajaya (PICC). -CARI Sumber: mStar Online
